From wingo Subject Re HST Servicing Mission Scheduled for Days In article Michael Corvin Regarding the feasability of retrieving the HST for repair and relaunching it Caution speculation mode engaged There is another consideration that hasn't been mentioned I expect that retrieving HST would involve 'damaging' it considerably in order to return it to its cradle in the cargo Most of the deployed items antennas and especially the solar arays probably are not retractable into their fully stowed position even by They would have to be removed by the The only advantage that this might yield is that we could put new panels on that don't 'ring' due to thermal cycle I also expect that as has been discussed the landing loads on the HST optics structure is a big issue but that the reentry loads are much less Can the moveable optical components even be re caged I assume that they were caged for launch It would be nice if someone here from the HST program was talking instead of all the speculation that is going on From what I understand from Frank Six of the Marshall Space Flight Center there is no insrmountable problem in bringing HST IT was designed that way to begin Also it is my understanding that the solar arrays WILL be one of the items replaced on this The originals were built by Brit Aerospace and I think the new ones are I am currently working with the guys at MSFC that are in charge is the HST power system although I have not spoken with them in a long time about Dennis University of Alabama in Huntsville